Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```cpp
#include <string>
#include <iostream>
#include <regex>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::regex markdown_regex("\\|([^|]+)\\|");
    std::smatch match;

    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, markdown_regex)) {
        std::string link = match[1];
        html += "<a href=\"" + link + "\">" + link + "</a><br>";
    }

    html += "<html><body>";
    html += markdown;
    html += "</body></html>";

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "This is a **bold** text. [Link to another page](https://example.com).";
    std::string html = markdown_to_html(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```
In this function, we first define a regular expression to match markdown formatting, specifically the `|` character followed by a non-`|` character. We then use `std::regex_search` to find all matches in the input `markdown` string.

For each match, we extract the link text and convert it to an HTML link. We then append this link to the `html` string.

Finally, we append the original markdown text to the `html` string and close the HTML tags. The resulting `html` string is returned.

In the `main` function, we demonstrate how to use the `markdown_to_html` function by passing in a sample markdown string and printing the resulting HTML string to the console.

