In TypeScript, you can use the `readonly` keyword to assert that a value will not change its type after it is initialized. This can help you ensure that a value will only have a specific type, even though it may have multiple types in theory.

For example, let's say you have a function that takes an array of strings and an array of numbers, and you want to assert that the function will only receive arrays that have the same length:
```
function processArrays(strings: string[], numbers: number[]) {
  // Do something with the arrays
}
```
To assert that the `strings` and `numbers` parameters will only have arrays of the same length, you can use the `readonly` keyword:
```
function processArrays(strings: readonly string[], numbers: readonly number[]) {
  // Do something with the arrays
}
```
The `readonly` keyword tells the TypeScript type system that the values of these parameters will not be changed after they are initialized, so they will only have the specific types you have specified.

You can also use the `readonly` keyword with interfaces to assert that a value will only have a specific type:
```
interface MyInterface {
  readonly prop1: string;
  readonly prop2: number;
}
```
In this case, the `MyInterface` type will only allow values that have a `prop1` of type `string` and a `prop2` of type `number`.

